ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorophore and quencher generally shows static and dynamic type of quenching however, the most definite method for distinguish between static and dynamic quenching is fluorescence life time measurement. If the mechanism is dynamic, then τ0/ τ = F0/F and the lifetime of N-CDs were reducing by metal ions and for static quenching τ0/ τ = 1 and there will be no change or slight change in fluorescence life time between N-CDs and metal ions [59]. For the identification of quenching mechanism between N-CDs and Cr6+ and Mn7+ metal ion fluorescence decay (life time) experiment was carried out and herein the life time of different concentration of Cr6+ and Mn7+ were studied with N-CD. The life time decay of pristine N-CDs was 397.60 pico second (ps), for Mn7+ life time decay was 477.18 ps, 4.77.18 ps, 357.74 ps, and 437.36 ps respectively (Fig. 7
                           a). Similarly, for Cr6+ life time decay value were 477.18 ps, 477.18 ps, 477.18 ps, and 437.36 ps respectively as shown in Fig. 7b all the data of life time decay indicated that the value of τ0/τ for both Cr6+ and Mn7+ is ∼ 1 which indicating that quenching of fluorescence with Cr6+ and Mn7+ might be static process. (SEE Fig. 8.
                           ).
